Red Wine Data Exploration and Summary

by Eric Spitler

Introduction

This report explores a dataset containing 11 variables on the chemical properties of 1,599 red wines. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent). The 13th variable listed in the dataset dimensions below is an index column.

Exploration Goal

I want to understand how the chemical properties of red wine relate to quality rating. Which properties correlate most with the highest and lowest rated wines? Are there any interesting relationships between the various chemical properties of the wines?

Histogram of Quality

All of the wines in the dataset have a rating between 3 and 8, with most rated 5 or 6.

Histograms of all chemical properties of the wines

Fixed acidity is right skewed with a mean that appears to be around 8 or 9.

Volatile acidity is strongly right skewed. A few wines have a volatile acidity level roughly three times the mean.

Citric acid is tightly grouped in the bottom 50% of the range. The distribution has a skinny tail at the top of the range.

Residual sugar has a very skinny long tail. A few wines in the dataset have a significantly higher residual sugar level than nearly all of the rest of the wines.

The chloride levels for the majority of the wines is tightly distributed with a long skinny tail on the right.

The free sulfur dioxide distribution is right skewed with a fat long tail on the right.

Very few wines have a total sulfur dioxide level that is significantly higher than the rest of the wines. This is another right skewed distribution.

Free sulfur dioxide is roughlt normally distributed. There is a wide range of free sulfur dioxide levels across the wines.

pH also is roughly normally distributed.

Sulphate levels are very right skewed with a long skinny tail. A few wines have sulphate levels 3-4x higher than the mean.

Alcohol is right skewed but there is a fat right tail, so there is a number of wines throughout the distribution of alcohol levels.

I want to compare the chemical properties for wines with the worst and best quality ratings and see if this helps me identify which properties to examine more closely.

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

There are 1599 red wines in the data set, with 12 features (quality, fixed acidity, volatile acidity, citric acid, residual sugar, chlorides, free sulfur dioxide, total sulfur dioxide, and density). The quality rating is an ordered factor, and while it is a numerical variable, it is really a categorical variable.

  • Most wines have a quality rating of 5 or 6. None of the wines were rated as low as 0, 1, or 2. None of them were rated as high as 9 or 10.

  • The mean value for each chemical property is as follows
    • fixed acidity - 8.32
    • volatile acidity - 0.5278
    • citric acid - 0.271
    • residual sugar - 2.539
    • chlorides - 0.08747
    • free sulfur dioxide - 15.87
    • total sulfur dioxide - 46.47
    • density - 0.9967
    • pH - 3.311
    • sulphates - 0.6581
    • alcohol - 10.42
    • quality - 5.636

  • Density and pH are both normally distributed, and the distributions of the other chemical properties have varying degrees of right-skewness.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

The main feature of the dataset is quality. My interest in examining the data is to understand the chemical properties of the wines that correlate with a wine receiving a specific expert quality rating.

What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your

investigation into your feature(s) of interest? I want to further explore the relationships between quality and volatile acidity, citric acid, chlorides, pH, sulphates, and alcohol. This is because for each of these chemical properties there is a linear trend from the mean value for wines with a quality rating of 3, to the dataset mean, to the mean value for wines with a quality rating of 8. My hypothesis is that these chemical properties will help explain the quality ratings of the wines.

Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I did not create any new variables.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions?

Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form
of the data? If so, why did you do this? Since the dataset was already very tidy, I didn’t need to change anything.

Bivariate Plots Section

Looking at scatter plots for each chemical property I want examine more closely vs. quality lets me quickly see how each property is distributed for each quality rating.

The distribution of volatile acidity is the lowest and tightest for the highest rated wines.

Citric acid doesn’t tell a strong story.

The distribution of chlorides for the highest rated wines is the tighest and lowest of all.

All quality ratings have a wide range of pH values.

Wines rated 3 and 4 have some of the lowest means sulphates. The distribution of sulphates in the highest rated wines are tightly grouped.

While each rating has relatively wide distribution of alcohol levels, in general, as alcohol goes up, quality rating goes up.

Let’s look at a correlation plot of the chemical properties and quality. The plot will also give a brief overview of any other interesting relationships between any of the variables.

The strongest correlation is between alcohol and quality, besides the correlation between pH and citric acid, which makes intuitive sense, since more acid means a lower pH.

Because of the lack of strong relationships in the above correlation plot, I’m curious to look at all the variables

I was wondering if quality and residual sugar had any relationship. Since the reviewers are experts, not casual wine drinkers, sweetness doesn’t play a factor here. The correlation coefficient is 0.01!

Leaving out relationships between pH and other acidity properties, the strongest correlations among chemical properties exist between density and fixed acidity, and between sulphates and chlorides.

Quality, volatile acidity, and alcohol share relatively high correlations, so I was curious to see them graphed together.

The lowest rated wines all have very low ratios of alcohol to volatile acidity.

I’m curious to see if the proprtion of sulfur dioxide that is ‘free’ is any different across quality ratings.

Volatile acidity negatively correlates with quality and fixed acidity correlates positively, albeit weakly. I’m curious if the ratio of volatile to fixed acidity relates interestingly with quality

With one exception, the highest rated wines have a low ratio of volatile to fixed acidity.

Bivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in
the dataset? The strongest (although not really that strong) correlations between quaility and chemical properties exists with alcohol (r = 0.48), volatile acidity (r = -0.39) , sulphates (r = 0.25), and citric acid (r = 0.23). Of the chemical properties, only alcohol has what qualifies as a moderately strong relationship. Volatile acidity is right on the edge of having a moderately strong negative relationship with quality.

More than any other quality rating, the worst rated wines all shared a low ratio of alcohol to volatile acidity. The lowest ratio of alcohol to volatile acidity of all belonged to wine with a quality rating of 3.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features

(not the main feature(s) of interest)? The few strong relationships between chemical properties exist between

  • Fixed acidity and density: r = 0.67
  • Fixed acidity and citric acid: r = 0.67 (yes, both are 0.67) The more of a specific acid, the higher the overall acid.
  • Alcohol and density: r = -0.50 This makes sense because water’s density is 997 kg/m^3 and ethanol’s density is 789 kg/m^3, so the higher the proportion of alcohol in the wine, the lower the density will be.

Examining the ratio of volatile acidity to fixed acidity in the wines showed that all but one of the highest rated wines shared a low ratio. All the other quality ratings had wide distributions of this ratio.

What was the strongest relationship you found?

The strongest relationship is a tie between the relationships with fixed acidity and density and fixed acidity and citric acid. The strongest relationship with quality, the main feature of interest is with alcohol.

Multivariate Plots Section

A moderately strong linear relationship is visible here, but we can see that there are no strong groupings of quality in the data. The dominance of 5 and 6 quality rated wines is also apparent.

We can clearly see that there is no linear relationship between density and fixed acidity, even though it looked promising in the bivariate analysis. We see that most wine are under 1.0 for density and 0.15 for fixed acidity, with the larger subsets, 5 and 6 having more outliers.

Here we can see a concentration 5-rated wines in the lower-left quadrant, but other than that there’s not much of a relationship apparent.

Multivariate Analysis

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the

investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of
looking at your feature(s) of interest? None of the relationships between chemical properties and quality that I explored showed any strong interactions. This is an interesting dynamic in the dataset.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?

The linearity of the relationship between density and fixed acidity was surprising. There may be some underlying chemical principals that explains this, but this was not obvious at the outset. I was surprised that were wasn’t an interaction of chemical properties that related more strongly to quality.

Reflection

The red wine dataset contains 11 chemical properties and an expert quality rating for 1599 wines. Using R made it easy to quickly acquaint myself with the dataset and begin exploring relationship in the data. Since this dataset had one main variable of interest, quality, it made sense to compare quality to all the chemical properties. It was fairly easy to see some trends in the relationships between quality and a few chemical properties. In examining the relationships between the chemical properties, the strongest relationship is between fixed acidity and density. There is also a moderately strong relationship between fixed acidity and citric acid, but this is to be expected.

In examining the data, I set out to focus my bivariate analyis on the chemical properties that had a linear trend from the mean of the lowest rated wines to the dataset mean to the mean of the highest rated wines. This lead me quickly to some moderately explanatory graphs, but again, nothing that was terribly strong and clear.

It was a bit frustrating looking for relationship in the data in general. There was no ‘smoking gun’ or big, obvious story in the data. It would be interesting to examine a dataset with ratings from a single expert and try to determine what role the preferences of the expert rater plays in the relationships between chemical properties and quality rating. It would also be interesting to compare ratings of untrained wine drinkes to those of experts for the same wines. I have read articles in the past that highlighted the inabilities of wine raters to consistently rate the same wine. This dynamic may contribute to the fact that the chemical property with the strongest correlation to quality was alcohol, which doesn’t seem like a property that would strongly effect the quality of the wine within a reasonable range.

To investigate the dataset further, I would build a linear model to understand which variables or interactions of variables best explain the quality ratings of the wines. A dataset with wines from more regions outside Portugal might provide less skewed distributions for the chemical properties, which could enhance the predictive power of a linear model.
